s, technicians, and others, Powell emphasizes the generative potential of Navajo resistance to articulate a vision of autonomy in the face of twenty-first-century colonial conditions. Ultimately, Powell situates local Navajo struggles over energy technology and infrastructure within broader sociocultural life, debates over global climate change, and tribal, federal, and global politics of extraction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCoal-fired power plantsxEconomic aspectszNavajo Nation, Arizona, New Mexico & Utah. 0aCoal-fired power plantsxEnvironmental aspectszNavajo Nation, Arizona, New Mexico & Utah. 0aEnergy developmentxPolitical aspectszNavajo Nation, Arizona, New Mexico & Utah. 0aPolitical ecologyzNavajo Nation, Arizona, New Mexico & Utah. 0aPower resourcesxEconomic aspectszNavajo Nation, Arizona, New Mexico & Utah. 0aPower resourcesxEnvironmental aspectszNavajo Nation, Arizona, New Mexico & Utah. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082236988240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372295/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles